{"title_page": "George Dassios", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = George Dassios\n| image       = Profile_photograph_of_Prof._George_Dassios_in_2018.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = George Dassios\n| birth_name  = Georgios Dassios\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1946|01|22}}\n| birth_place = Patras, Greece\n| residence   =\n| citizenship = [[Greece|Greek]]\n| nationality = [[Greece|Greek]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    = University of Patras\n| occupation  =\n| title       = Emeritus Professor, Chemical Engineering Department\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    = 2\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = http://www.chemeng.upatras.gr/en/personel/faculty/en/gdassios\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''George Dassios ''' ({{lang-el|\u0393\u03b5\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}}) is a Greek mathematician, scholar and corresponding member of the Academy of Athens. \n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in 1946, in [[Patras]], [[Greece]], where he attended primary and secondary education. He received his Bachelor's degree from the Department of Mathematics of the [[University of Athens]] in 1970 and continued his postgraduate studies at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] where he received his [[Master of Science]] in 1972 and his [[Ph.D.]] in 1975 in [[Applied Mathematics]].\n\nIn 1980 he was awarded the title of Applicant of Applied Mathematics at the [[National Technical University of Athens]]. In 1981, at age of 35, he was elected a Professor at the Department of Mathematics of the [[University of Patras]] and in 1989 he accepted an invitation from the Department of Chemical Engineering at the same University.\n \nHe has taught and been invited to give research seminars at more than 120 universities mainly in the USA and Europe, but also Japan, Korea, Finland, and Brazil.\n\nHis work includes 168 research papers published in major international scientific journals. He has also authored 21 textbooks and two research monographs, one published by [[Oxford University Press]] in 2000 and one by [[Cambridge University Press]] in 2012. He has also announced more than 200 scientific papers at international conferences.\n\nHe has participated, but also led as a scientific director, dozens of research programs in Greece and abroad. He was the scientific director of the PANEGO program for early diagnosis of craniocerebral injuries and the recognition of particle shape in biological suspensions selected by the [[European Commission]] in 2004 as the most successful research project funded by the [[European Commission]] in Greece.<ref> [https://ec.europa.eu/regional_policy/en/projects/greece/when-life-hangs-by-a-threadmedical-engineering-on-the-cutting-edge  When life hangs by a thread:Medical engineering on the cutting edge]</ref>\n\nHe has supervised 23 doctoral dissertations. Most of his doctoral students are currently professors at universities in Greece and abroad.\n\nHe is a member of 23 scientific Societies.\n\nDuring the [[International Mathematical Olympiad]], which took place in [[Athens]], in 2004, he was chairman of the International Commission, which consisted of the leaders of all participating countries.\n\nHe has been involved for more than 25 years in examination committees of the [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs (Greece)]], the State Scholarship Foundation and the [[Supreme Council for Civil Personnel Selection]]. Since 2014, he has been the president of the independent National Exams Organization of the [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs (Greece)]].\n\nIn 2017 he was elected as corresponding member of the [[Academy of Athens]] in the Chair of Applied Analysis.\n\nToday, he is Emeritus Professor at the [[University of Patras]] and an Honorary Researcher at the [[Foundation for Research & Technology \u2013 Hellas]].\n\n== Honors ==\n* [[Academy of Athens]], Award, for his work on the problem of [[Magnetoencephalography]] in [[elliptical geometry]] (2004).\n* [[European Union]], Marie Curie Chair of Excellence Professorship in Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physic, [[University of Cambridge]] (2005).\n* [[Scouts_of_Greece]], Scout Order of The Silver Phoenix (2018).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = George Dassios\n| image       = Profile_photograph_of_Prof._George_Dassios_in_2018.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = George Dassios\n| birth_name  = Georgios Dassios\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1946|01|22}}\n| birth_place = Patras, Greece\n| residence   =\n| citizenship = [[Greece|Greek]]\n| nationality = [[Greece|Greek]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    = University of Patras\n| occupation  =\n| title       = Emeritus Professor, Chemical Engineering Department\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    = 2\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = http://www.chemeng.upatras.gr/en/personel/faculty/en/gdassios\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''George Dassios ''' ({{lang-el|\u0393\u03b5\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2}}) is a Greek mathematician, scholar and corresponding member of the Academy of Athens. \n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in 1946, in [[Patras]], [[Greece]], where he attended primary and secondary education. He received his Bachelor's degree from the Department of Mathematics of the [[University of Athens]] in 1970 and continued his postgraduate studies at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] where he received his [[Master of Science]] in 1972 and his [[Ph.D.]] in 1975 in [[Applied Mathematics]].\n\nIn 1980 he was awarded the title of Applicant of Applied Mathematics at the [[National Technical University of Athens]]. In 1981, at age of 35, he was elected a Professor at the Department of Mathematics of the [[University of Patras]] and in 1989 he accepted an invitation from the Department of Chemical Engineering at the same University.\n \nHe has taught and been invited to give research seminars at more than 120 universities mainly in the USA and Europe, but also Japan, Korea, Finland, and Brazil.\n\nHis work includes 168 research papers published in major international scientific journals. He has also authored 21 textbooks and two research monographs, one published by [[Oxford University Press]] in 2000 and one by [[Cambridge University Press]] in 2012. He has also announced more than 200 scientific papers at international conferences.\n\nHe has participated, but also led as a scientific director, dozens of research programs in Greece and abroad. He was the scientific director of the PANEGO program for early diagnosis of craniocerebral injuries and the recognition of particle shape in biological suspensions selected by the [[European Commission]] in 2004 as the most successful research project funded by the [[European Commission]] in Greece.<ref> [https://ec.europa.eu/regional_policy/en/projects/greece/when-life-hangs-by-a-threadmedical-engineering-on-the-cutting-edge  When life hangs by a thread:Medical engineering on the cutting edge]</ref>\n\nHe has supervised 23 doctoral dissertations. Most of his doctoral students are currently professors at universities in Greece and abroad.\n\nHe is a member of 23 scientific Societies.\n\nDuring the [[International Mathematical Olympiad]], which took place in [[Athens]], in 2004, he was chairman of the International Commission, which consisted of the leaders of all participating countries.\n\nHe has been involved for more than 25 years in examination committees of the [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs (Greece)]], the State Scholarship Foundation and the [[Supreme Council for Civil Personnel Selection]]. Since 2014, he has been the president of the independent National Exams Organization of the [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs (Greece)]].\n\nIn 2017 he was elected as corresponding member of the [[Academy of Athens]] in the Chair of Applied Analysis.\n\nToday, he is Emeritus Professor at the [[University of Patras]] and an Honorary Researcher at the [[Foundation for Research & Technology \u2013 Hellas]].\n\n== Honors ==\n* [[Academy of Athens]], Award, for his work on the problem of [[Magnetoencephalography]] in [[elliptical geometry]] (2004).\n* [[European Union]], Marie Curie Chair of Excellence Professorship in Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physic, [[University of Cambridge]] (2005).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Patrinosss", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Dassios"}
